Key Git Concepts

Repository - A Folder where Git tracks your project and its history.
Clone - Make a copy of the remote repository on your compute
Stage - Tell Git which changes you want to save next.
Commit - Save a snapshot of your staged changes.
Branch - Work on different versions of features at the same time
Merge - Combine changes from different branches.
Pull - Get the latest changes from a remote repository
Push - Send your changes to a remote repository 

Set up name and email global in git:

git config --global user.name "Sample"
git config --global user.email "Sample@sample.com"

--global for every repo on your compute
--local (default) current repo


git config --list
git config user.name
git config user.email
git config code.editor

git config --global --unset user.name 
git config --global --unset user.email
git config --global --unset code.editor

Config Levels:

git config --system  (all users)
git config --global (current user)
git config --local (current repo)

Local settings only apply to the current repo - git config user.name "Project Name" 
Global settings apply to all repositories for the current user - git config --global user.name "Global Name"
System settings apply to all repositories for all users - git config --system user.name "System Name"

Initialize Git 

git init - git creats a hidden folder called .git inside your project 

what is repository?

a git repository is a folder that git tracks for changes, the repository stores all your projects history and versions.

ls -a - show hidden .git folder

ls - list files in the folder

pwd - to check the current directory

git status - check which files are tracked

what is a tracked file? 

a tracked file is a file that Git is watching for changes, to make a file tracked, you need to add it to the staging area.

what is the staging environment? 

the staging environment or staging area is like a waiting room for your changes.

you use it to tell git exactly which files you want to include in your next commit.

this gives you control over what goes into your project history.

git add <file> : stage file
git add --all or git add -A : stage all changes
git status : see what staged
git rm --cached <file> - unstage file

what is commit? 

A commit is like a save point in your project.

it records a snapshop of your files at a certain time, with a message describing what changed.

git commit -m "message" : commit staged changes with a message
git commit -a -m "message" : commit all tracked changes 
git log - see commit history
git commit (no -m)
git commit --allow-empty -m "Start project" : create an empty commity
git commit --no-edit : use previous commit message (no editor)
git commit --amend --no-edit : quickly add staged changes to last commit, keep message
git commit -m "message but forgot to git add a file, just add it commit again. or use commit --amend to add it your last commit
typo: git commit --ammend -m "corrected message" to fix the last commit message
accidentally commited the wrong files? 
git reset --soft HEAD~1 to undo the last commit and keep your changes staged

git log --oneline

git log --stat : to see which files chnaged in each commit

key commands for tagging

